%md
###Overview
k-means clustering has often been used for applications in Machine Learning, but its use in Earth Science is relatively new. In this notebook we will apply pyspark's mllib implementation of k-means clustering to group individual grid points together in a dataset based on similar climate regimes. We will do so for this particular example using the standard deviation and skewness of surface air temperature time series.

####Useful Reference
Loikith, P. C., B. R. Lintner, J. Kim, H. Lee, J. D. Neelin, and D. E. Waliser, 2013: Classifying reanalysis surface temperature probability density functions (PDFs) over North America with cluster analysis, Geophys. Res. Lett., 40, doi:10.1002/grl.50688. ([PDF](http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/grl.50688/pdf))

####Accessing the data
For this example we will be using the NASA MERRA reanalysis daily mean surface air temperature dataset. The spatial resolution is 0.5 degrees latitude by 0.67 degrees longitude, with a temporal coverage of 1979-2011. The raw data has already been subset into one quarter of the globe primarily spanning North America and includes only days falling in January. %pyspark
from netCDF4 import Dataset
nc = Dataset('/home/workshop/pdf_clustering/tas_MERRA_NA_daily_January_1979-2011.nc')
tas = nc.variables['tasjan'][:]
lats = nc.variables['lat'][:]
lons = nc.variables['lon'][:]

%md
####Preparing the data
Before applying kmeans clustering, we must properly prepare the data first. This entails converting the raw temperature values to anomalies (deviations from the mean climatological state) and then removing longterm linear trends.

paragraphs.title: Step 2: Calculate temperature anomalies and Remove Longterm Linear Trends
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import numpy as np
import scipy.signal as signal

def detrend_daily_data(data, years, month):
    '''
    Detrend a daily climate time series for one month.
    This will remove the climatology for each day as well as directly remove
    longterm linear trends at each grid point.

    Input:
        data - 3D numpy array with dimensions (days, lats, lons)
        years - 1D numpy array of years spanning the time series
        month - The month for the given time series (1-Jan, 12-Dec)

    Output:
        detrended_data - Detrended time series (days, lats, lons)

    Note: February (month=2) not supported yet.
    '''
    # Reshape the data based on the month
    days_by_month = [31, 29, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31]
    mdays = days_by_month[month-1]
    nyears = len(years)

    # TODO: Support for Feb if desired
    if month == 2:
        raise ValueError('February (month=2) not currently supported')

    # Reshape to (year, day of year, lat, lon) to easily calculate
    # daily climatology
    data = data.reshape(nyears, mdays, *data.shape[1:])

    # Subtract daily climatology from original data to obtain anomalies
    clim = data.mean(axis=0)
    data -= clim

    # Remove longterm linear trends
    data = data.reshape(mdays*nyears, *data.shape[2:])
    detrended_data = signal.detrend(data, axis=0)
    return detrended_data

years = np.arange(1979, 2012)
month = 1
detrended_data = detrend_daily_data(tas, years, month)

%md
####Determining the inputs For k-means
We may choose to use an arbitrary number of variables defined at each grid point as our input for k-means clustering. In this example we will use two PDF moments (Standard Deviation and Skewness) as our input, which are calculated from the detrended anomaly timeseries at each grid point below:

We may choose to use an arbitrary number of variables defined at each grid point as our input for k-means clustering. In this example we will use two PDF moments (Standard Deviation and Skewness) as our input, which are calculated from the detrended anomaly timeseries at each grid point below:

paragraphs.title: Step 3: Calculate the PDF moments
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from scipy.stats import stats

def calc_moments(data):
    '''
    Determine standard deviation and skewness of input data

    Input:
        data - 3D numpy array with dimensions (days, lats, lons)

    Output:
        std, skew - 2nd and 3rd PDF moments respectively for
        each grid point (lats, lons)
    '''
    std = np.std(data, axis=0)
    skew = stats.skew(data, axis=0)
    return std, skew
    
std, sk = calc_moments(detrended_data)

%md
####Perform k-means clustering on the PDF moments
We are now finally ready to perform k-means clustering using the PDF moments calculated in the previous step as our input. The choice of k is in fact an arbitrary one, but for our purposes we will find that k=5 should produce the most physically meaningful clusters. Here we will use pyspark's mllib implementation of k-means clustering to get the job done.

paragraphs.title: Step 4: Perform K-means clustering on the PDF Moments
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from pyspark.mllib.clustering import KMeans

def kmeans_clustering(k, m1, m2, **kwargs):
    '''
    Perform k-means clustering

    Input:
        k - Number of clusters (int)
        m1, m2 - The PDF moments for each grid point (lat, lon) or (grid points)
        (Optional) kwargs - kwargs - see pyspark.mllib.clustering.KMeans.train() for more options

    Output:
        centroids - locations of cluster centroids in m1, m2 space (k, 2)
        labels - index array which assigns each grid point to a centroid
    '''
    # Ensure moments are 1D before clustering. The input to kmeans must
    # have a shape of (m, n) where m is the number of grid points and
    # n is the number of dimensions (in this case 1 for each moment)
    m1 = m1.ravel()
    m2 = m2.ravel()

    # Place processed moments into input array
    input_array = np.array(zip(m1, m2))
    rdd = sc.parallelize(input_array)
    model = KMeans.train(rdd, k, **kwargs)
    centroids = np.array(model.centers)
    temp_labels = np.array(model.predict(rdd).collect())
    
    # Sort centroids and labels by centroid distance to origin
    dist = (centroids**2).sum(axis=1)
    sortidx = np.argsort(dist)
    centroids = centroids[sortidx]
    labels = np.zeros_like(temp_labels)
    for i in range(k):
        labels[temp_labels==sortidx[i]] = i
    return centroids, labels
    
k = 5
centroids, labels = kmeans_clustering(k, std, sk, maxIterations=300,
                                      initializationMode='kmeans',
                                      seed=0)

%md
####Visualizing the results
There are two outputs from k-means clustering. First we have `centroids`, which are a set of points defined in n-dimensional space representing the locations of the cluster centroids. In this case, we entered n=2 input variables into k-means with k=5, so this variable is an array of 5 points denoting (Standard Deviation, Skewness). The `labels` array contains the cluster number assigned to each grid point which are denoted by the respective indices of the centroids array (eg 0-4). We will now produce a figure which contains (1) The cluster numbers color coded on a map (2) A scatter plot of the clusters over the entire grid with the centroid locations denoted, and (3) contour maps of standard deviation and skewness. The resulting figure should be consistent with Loikith et al., 2013.

%md
####Probability Density Functions (PDFs) of each cluster
Given these results so far, are the shapes of the underlying distributions for each cluster consistent with what we expect? To find out, we will approximate the PDFs using histograms with 152 bins. Following Loikith et al. 2013, we will also apply a base 10 logarithm to the bin counts to weigh the tails of the distributions more heavily. The following code can be used to define these histograms at each gridpoint. Note that the solid lines are the mean probabilities for each bin while the shaded area denotes one standard deviation from the mean.

paragraphs.title: Generate histograms
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def make_histograms(data, nbins, logarithmic=True, probabilities=True):
    '''
    Make histograms of time series at each grid point
    
    Input:
        data - input gridded data, dimensions (time, lat, lon)
        nbins - Number of equally spaced bins in the histogram
        (Optional) logarithmic - Take log10 of bin counts if True
        (Optional) probabilitis - Divide bin counts by length of time series
                                  if True
    Output:
        hist - histogram bin counts at each grid point, 
               shape (# of grid points, # of bins)
        bins - Bin edges array
    '''
    hist = []
    bins = np.histogram(data, bins=152)[1]
    ndays = float(data.shape[0])
    for i in range(len(lats)):
        for j in range(len(lons)):
            hist.append(np.histogram(data[:, i, j], bins=bins, density=False)[0])
    
    hist = np.array(hist, dtype='float32')
    
    # We may divide the bin counts by the total number of days in the time series
    # to get a probability associated with each bin
    if probabilities:
        hist /= ndays
        
    if logarithmic:
        hist = np.log10(hist)
        
        # Because log10(0) is -inf, we also need to set the bin count to a valid value
        hist[np.isinf(hist)] = -(np.log10(ndays) + 0.5)
        
    return hist, bins

hist, bins = make_histograms(detrended_data, 152)

paragraphs.title: Plot Histograms
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def visualize_histograms(centroids, labels, hist, bins, units='K', ptitle='', cmap='rainbow_r'):
    '''
    Plot PDFs for each cluster

    Input:
        centroids - locations of cluster centroids (k, 2)
        labels - group number for each grid point (gridpoints)
        hist - Array containing histogram info for each grid point (gridpoints, nbins)
        bins - Bin edges array (nbins)
        (Optional) units - Units of the source data (string)
        (Optional) ptitle - Plot title (string)
    '''
    clusters = labels + 1
    k = centroids.shape[0]

    # Set up the color scaling
    cmap = plt.get_cmap(cmap)
    norm = mpl.colors.Normalize(vmin=1, vmax=k)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8.5, 5.5))

    # Cluster PDFs
    anom = 0.5*(bins + np.roll(bins, -1))[:-1]
    colorpicker = mpl.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=cmap)
    for i in range(1, k+1):
        vals = hist[clusters==i]
        pdf = vals.mean(axis=0)
        std = vals.std(axis=0)
        color = colorpicker.to_rgba(i)
        plt.plot(anom, pdf, color=color)
        plt.fill_between(anom, pdf-std, pdf+std, facecolor=color,
                        edgecolor=color, alpha=0.35)
                        
    plt.xlabel('Anomaly [%s]' %units)
    plt.ylabel(r'$\log_{10}$ Probability')
    plt.xlim(xmin=-30, xmax=30)
    plt.ylim(ymin=-3.5, ymax=0)
    plt.title('Cluster PDFs - %s' %ptitle)
    show(plt)

visualize_histograms(centroids, labels, hist, bins, ptitle='MERRA')

You may use the logarithmic bin counts at each grid point that are already generated in the variable `hist`. Plot your results using calls to `visualize_clusters()` and `visualize_histograms()`. Are these results similar to those shown when using two moments as inputs to k-means instead? To get started, you may use the template in the cell below. The code to visualize the clusters and the mean PDFs is also included in the denoted cells.

paragraphs.title: Exercise 2 Discussion
paragraphs.text:
%md
You should find that using too few or too many clusters creates some difficulty in physically interpreting the results. With k=5 each cluster is in fact physically explainable. With too many clusters the differences between each of them become more difficult to both physically and statistically distinguish, and with too few clusters the you may overlook some important physical features. The point of this exercise is to demonstrate that users should not blindly pick one value of k if they were to apply clustering to their own data. It is necessary to test several different values of k, which could be seen as a drawback to the clustering approach for PDF visualization.

###Lessons Learned
 - k-means can be used to group sets of points together into clusters by similar characteristics
 - The number of characteristics to use can range from a few (PDF moments) to many (histogram bin counts)
 - Although seemingly more complex, results from the histogram bin count method were consistent with the moments-based method
 - A drawback is that the choice of k (number of clusters) is arbitrary

###Additional SciSpark use cases for cluster analysis of climate data
It should be noted that the examples shown here only demonstrated the use of spark in the computation of k-means. Additionally the input data from our netcdf file was already temporally subsetted for the month of January and spatially subsetted to include primarily North America outside of this notebook. In practice, greatly speeding up these operations in particular would be the greatest benefit from applying SciSpark to this problem since often times reanalysis datasets are defined within individual netcdf files for each year, month, day, or even hour! For the MERRA dataset used in this problem, the raw data was in fact split over 12,052 daily netcdf files, which can be quite difficult to process sequentially!
